## II. The Data Broker Loophole: Where Corporate Capture Meets Surveillance

The absence of comprehensive federal privacy law in the United States is the downstream product of the regulatory vacuum that Powell’s institutional project created and sustained across five decades. The data broker industry is the bastard child of that deregulatory project: a $250+ billion industry that exists in the gap between what the Fourth Amendment was meant to protect and what corporate lobbying has carved out.

The contrast with the European Union is foundational. The EU’s General Data Protection Regulation, implemented in 2018, requires explicit and informed consent before personal data is collected. It applies to any entity that processes personal data in the context of activities in the EU or that targets EU individuals — without revenue thresholds, without processing thresholds, without broker thresholds. There is no revenue threshold, processing threshold, or broker threshold. Violations carry administrative fines of up to €20 million or 4% of total worldwide annual turnover, whichever is higher.

The United States does not have a single, comprehensive federal data privacy law. Instead, data privacy regulations are a combination of sector-specific and state-level laws that govern how personal data is collected, processed, and shared. These regulations vary in scope and enforcement and often focus on specific industries such as healthcare, finance, and education. As of 2026, only four states — California, Oregon, Texas, and Vermont — require data brokers to register with state agencies and disclose their activities. Data brokers are third-party entities that purchase personal data, often unbeknownst to the individuals whose data is being traded. All data brokers that process data not collected directly from the data subjects themselves now have to register with these four states. However, it is not exactly straightforward for data subjects to delete their information from these brokers’ databases.

The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau proposed a rule on December 3, 2024, to limit the sale of key personal information — such as Social Security numbers and phone numbers — under its interpretation of the Fair Credit Reporting Act. The proposal was explicitly designed to counter threats of fraud, stalking, espionage, identity theft, and surveillance, including risks posed to public officials, military personnel, and survivors of domestic violence. However, the CFPB ultimately concluded that such a rule was “not necessary or appropriate at this time,” citing inconsistencies with its current interpretation of the FCRA.

In the EU, explicit and informed consent is required from individuals before their data is collected. However, in the United States, for the states that have privacy laws to date, in most cases personal data can be collected and used without needing to obtain prior consent, unless the data subject is a child. The main legal requirement is that data subjects be informed about data processing and their rights. The CCPA provides the chance to opt out as opposed to the GDPR’s specific need to opt in. The consequences of noncompliance reflect the gap: CCPA violators face civil penalties of up to $7,500 per intentional violation. The GDPR’s penalties reach into the billions. True consent to disclosure involves clear and voluntary agreement, in which consumers understand what will be collected and how it will be used. This is generally not mandated in the U.S.

And at the center of this patchwork is the gap that matters most: there is no federal law prohibiting law enforcement agencies from purchasing data that they would otherwise need a warrant to obtain.

A whole industry of data brokers buys up vast quantities of electronic information from cell phone apps and web browsers and sells it to advertisers who use that data to target ads. The same industry also sells that data, including bulk cell phone location data, to police departments and federal government agencies in ways that can reveal intimate details about Americans without a warrant.

The Supreme Court’s 2018 decision in *Carpenter v. United States* held that police need a warrant to obtain historical cell-site location information — the data generated as a cell phone automatically connects to nearby cell towers. The Court recognized that tracking a person’s movements over time is extremely invasive, that individuals have a reasonable expectation of privacy when it comes to the “all-encompassing record” of their whereabouts. This type of data, the Court wrote, gave the government “near perfect surveillance and allows it to travel back in time to retrace a person’s whereabouts, subject only to the five-year retention policies of most wireless carriers.” The Court held that Americans have a privacy right to their historical cell phone data since location information is highly revealing, and that if law enforcement wants to obtain location information on a particular individual for seven days or more, it must have a warrant.

Nevertheless, several government agencies have argued that the *Carpenter* decision applies only to the specific type of location data at issue in that case — historical cell-site location information — and that Fourth Amendment protections apply only when the government compels companies to disclose information, not when private companies sell or voluntarily disclose information to law enforcement. Based on these purported distinctions, agencies are continuing to purchase cell phone location data — without a warrant or any other legal process — in large volumes. The Supreme Court presumably will clarify *Carpenter*‘s applicability in due time, but for now, government agencies are relying heavily on data purchases to sidestep the Fourth Amendment’s central safeguard against abusive policing: the requirement that police obtain a warrant from a judge before invading a reasonable expectation of privacy.

The government’s position is that buying data is constitutionally different from seizing it. The practical effect is the same: your movements are tracked, your associations are mapped, your life is rendered transparent to the state — but no judge was asked, no warrant was issued, and no probable cause was established.

Unlike private entities, government agencies may purchase personal data to further their exercise of coercive powers, including the ability to deport, arrest, incarcerate, or even use lethal force. Unfettered government access to personal data without judicial or legislative oversight can exacerbate existing biases in law enforcement and intelligence practices, permitting speculative investigations on the basis of constitutionally protected categories and the targeting of marginalized communities. Evidence of this phenomenon abounds, from the Defense Department purchasing location data collected from prayer apps to monitor Muslim communities to police departments purchasing information to track racial justice protesters.

Among the main purveyors in this surveillance capitalism ecosystem are data brokers — companies that collect, assemble, and analyze personal information to create detailed profiles of individuals, which they then sell. Although most of these companies are not household names, they serve an ever-growing demand; the industry pulled in more than $250 billion in 2022. Data brokers collect information from various sources. They pay app developers to install code that siphons users’ data, including location information. They use cookies or other web trackers to capture online activity. They scrape information from public-facing sites, including social media platforms, often in violation of those platforms’ terms of service. They also collect information from public records and purchase data from a wide range of companies that collect and maintain personal information, including app developers, internet service providers, car manufacturers, advertisers, utility companies, supermarkets, and others.

**Local police and Fog Data Science.** A Virginia-based company called Fog Data Science sells a service that it bills as allowing police to see where a person was at any point in time over the past several years. This surveillance includes not only possible crime scenes but also homes, churches, workplaces, health clinics, or anywhere else. The data is collected and passed through a chain of businesses before ending up with law enforcement. First, personal location data is gathered via thousands of common apps that people use on Android and iOS phones, that people install for various purposes and may not suspect are gathering and sharing that information. Fog Data Science claims it collects 15 billion sets of data points daily from 250 million U.S. devices every month sourced from “tens of thousands” of mobile apps with tracking code included.

An investigation by the Electronic Frontier Foundation — conducted by a team of EFF experts led by Staff Technologist Bennett Cyphers, taking several months and more than 100 public records requests — uncovered a massive surveillance operation. EFF discovered that Fog has past or current contracts with at least 18 local, state, and federal law enforcement clients, while other agencies accepted free trials. Troublingly, records show Fog and some police agencies didn’t believe this surveillance implicated people’s Fourth Amendment rights and so they didn’t obtain a warrant before searching through people’s location data. And glaringly absent from the public records EFF received were any documents establishing policies or other limits about when and how police could and should deploy this massive digital dragnet.

Among the findings: In Chino, California, police used Fog’s service to do massive sweeps determining who was near minor theft and burglary scenes. In a rural Missouri murder investigation, Fog’s service was used to track a babysitter who was never a suspect — police built an extensive profile of her movements and activities using purchased data, only to find out later through witness testimony that the victim’s wife was responsible. In Greensboro, North Carolina, a crime analysis supervisor raised red flags about its constitutionality and later quit after his warnings were ignored. And in all these places and many more, police never seemed to set any rules for when and how this massive digital dragnet should or shouldn’t be used.

Fog sells subscriptions to its Fog Reveal search engine and it does not require law enforcement to obtain a warrant or subpoena before searching for and buying information from it. This gives police an easy way to pull up location records for a device, and track and identify the device owner from their home address and place of work — or, really, anywhere else they have visited with their cellphone. Fog’s subscription costs less than $10,000 — mass surveillance on a municipal budget.

EFF investigative researcher Beryl Lipton stated: “Police departments of all sizes have been using a system that stores and makes searchable the historical locations of individuals. This means that they could identify the phones — and, by extension, the people — that have been at a protest, a reproductive health center, a place of worship, or other locations and track them to the places they live. This violates our constitutional rights, especially when police do it without a warrant.”

Location records from brokers are typically unlinked to a device owner’s name. But tools exist that help law enforcement track where a device has gone, where it spends every night and where it goes during working hours, as EFF senior staff technologist Bill Budington noted. Despite claims by Fog and other data brokers that the information they sell doesn’t contain personally identifiable information because it’s limited to timestamps, location coordinates, and random unique identifiers, it doesn’t take too much police work to link this supposedly anonymized data to actual people. In post-*Roe* America, this means that law enforcement can bypass warrants for Google Maps queries to build a case against an individual seeking an abortion in a state where the procedure is now illegal.

**Federal agencies.** U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement began purchasing access to cell phone users’ digital location data through a data brokerage company called Venntel in 2018. The data had been collected from popular cell phone apps, including weather, shopping, and video game apps. ICE used Venntel’s service to track the movements of cell phone users in areas near the United States’ southern border. At one point, ICE discovered that cell phones were moving back and forth across a closed portion of the border in a straight line. They eventually determined that the phones were traveling through what was likely an underground smuggling tunnel that ran from a private home in Mexico to a closed Kentucky Fried Chicken restaurant in San Luis, Arizona. ICE passed this information to the local police department, which made an apparently pretextual traffic stop of Ivan Lopez, the KFC’s owner, finding large quantities of drugs.

The San Luis police kept any mention of the cell phone tracking out of their records and initially attributed their traffic stop of Lopez to an “equipment violation.” This is not abnormal. Government agents often obscure their purchases of constitutionally protected information by recreating the purchased information through more traditional and lawful means, like traffic stops. This process, though successful, raises obvious concerns about pervasive surveillance, deception, and the avoidance of public scrutiny. And, as with almost any surveillance technique, the innocent as well as the guilty have their lives scrutinized by the police.

These tracking companies hide from any public exposure or notice. The nonpublic nature of this surveillance places it far outside the scope of Fourth Amendment case law indicating that police officers can usually engage in lawful conduct that members of the public might undertake. Supreme Court case law generally requires a surveillance practice to not only be available to the public but also be widely used before its public nature eliminates Fourth Amendment protections. In *Kyllo v. United States*, the Supreme Court held that police needed a warrant before using infrared heat cameras to surveil a suspect’s house, even though these cameras were readily available to the public.

The online magazine Motherboard revealed that a data broker named X-Mode compiled geolocation data from a popular Muslim prayer app (Muslim Pro) and a Muslim dating app (Muslim Mingle), then sold this extremely sensitive data to the U.S. military through defense contractors. The Department of Homeland Security, ICE, and Customs and Border Protection used a commercial database from Venntel Inc. to obtain user location data to detect undocumented immigrants and monitor cell phone activity along the border. This location information — combined with other surveillance tools — was used to track, arrest, and even deport immigrants across the country. The U.S. Internal Revenue Service partnered with Venntel to identify and monitor potential criminal suspects in money-laundering, cyber, drug, and organized crime cases.

News reports indicate that the FBI, Secret Service, and Department of Defense have acquired smartphone location data without a warrant. Defense contractors purchased location data from popular Muslim prayer and Qur’an apps and dating apps. Several members of Congress made official inquiries into how this data has been utilized. Cell phone data was allegedly used to track Black Lives Matter protesters over the summer of 2020. Though it is uncertain exactly how cell phone data informed the FBI’s response to the protests, it is notable that the agency renegotiated its purchase contract with a data broker around the time of the demonstrations. The use of purchased data to target religious groups and protesters emphasizes the critical importance of the Fourth Amendment in protecting against discriminatory policing practices. It also underscores the chilling effect unrestricted surveillance has on other civil liberties, including religious freedom and the right to dissent.

Some police departments have attempted to circumvent bans on their use of facial recognition by purchasing facial recognition search results from third-party vendors.

**The legislative landscape.** Montana became the first state to close the data broker loophole for law enforcement in May 2025, with SB 282 preventing law enforcement from purchasing citizens’ data from data brokers when ordinarily they would need a warrant to access such information.

California Governor Gavin Newsom signed SB 361 into law on October 28, 2025, expanding the state’s data broker oversight.

Texas’s data broker registration law went into effect in March 2024. In June 2024, the Texas Attorney General’s Office sent letters to more than 100 companies notifying them of registration requirements. In December 2024, the AG followed up with six violation notices to companies that still hadn’t registered. The California Privacy Protection Agency similarly issued enforcement actions against two companies in November 2024 that failed to register.

The Protecting Americans’ Data from Foreign Adversaries Act of 2024 (PADFA) prohibits data brokers from selling personally identifiable sensitive data to certain foreign adversary countries — China, North Korea, Russia, and Iran — or to entities controlled by those countries. The law went into effect in June 2024. The Department of Justice issued a final rule at the end of 2024 that restricts and regulates additional foreign personal data transactions, with strict prohibitions on data brokerage defined more broadly than under PADFA.

In 2024, the FTC settled with two data brokers over allegations that the companies collected, retained, and sold consumers’ precise location data associated with “sensitive” locations without adequately verifying consumers’ consent.

At the federal level, the bipartisan Fourth Amendment Is Not For Sale Act would prohibit law enforcement and intelligence agencies from purchasing certain sensitive information from third-party sellers, including geolocation information, communications-related information protected under the Electronic Communications Privacy Act, and information obtained through illegitimate scraping practices. Under the bill, there are exceptions for emergencies, and agencies would still be able to obtain information using a warrant, court order, or subpoena. In 2024, a bipartisan majority in the U.S. House passed the Act. Several pieces of legislation that address the data broker loophole have support, including the Government Surveillance Reform Act, the SAFE Act, and the Protect Liberty and End Warrantless Surveillance Act.

Over 130 civil society organizations signed a letter urging Congress to include closing the data broker loophole in FISA 702 reauthorization, citing the “unprecedented expansion of warrantless mass surveillance that is sweeping up the private information of communities across America” and the potential for the loophole to be used “to supercharge AI-powered surveillance.”

When Senator Ron Wyden asked FBI Director Kash Patel in early 2026 if he would commit to not buying Americans’ location data, Patel declined, saying the FBI “uses all tools” and “we do purchase commercially available information that’s consistent with the Constitution and the laws under the Electronic Communications Privacy Act, and it has led to some valuable intelligence for us.”

Representative Warren Davidson (R-Ohio) told NPR: “This is one of those issues that really doesn’t break on party lines. You’re collecting data that really you would never get a warrant for, that kind of a broad dragnet sweep under normal warrant requirements.” He teamed up with conservative Senator Mike Lee and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Wyden on bicameral bipartisan FISA reform legislation.

Jake Laperruque, deputy director of the Security and Surveillance Project at the Center for Democracy and Technology, stated that purchasing bulk data from data brokers is “very much not what Congress intended when it said we are banning bulk collection. It wasn’t, you know, ‘do bulk collection, but also pay taxpayer money for it.’ It was ‘don’t do bulk collection.’” He added that the idea that law enforcement can purchase information from data brokers they would normally need a warrant for doesn’t make sense, particularly since it is often possible to identify individuals from supposedly anonymized data.

Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei warned in a statement in February 2026 that records the government can purchase can be used by AI to assemble “a comprehensive picture of any person’s life — automatically and at massive scale.” Amodei’s unwillingness to allow Anthropic’s technology to be used for domestic mass surveillance or autonomous weapons led to a major fight with the Pentagon, which says a private company cannot dictate how the government lawfully uses its technology.

Jeramie D. Scott, senior counsel and director of the Surveillance and Oversight Program at the Electronic Privacy Information Center, told NPR that government data purchases without a warrant are “contributing to an ever-expanding infrastructure of private sector surveillance that is hurtling us into a dystopian surveillance society.”

Privacy advocates say the upcoming FISA reauthorization debate is the best chance to close the so-called data broker loophole. “This is very likely the only chance that Congress has this year to vote for meaningful privacy protections,” said Sean Vitka, executive director of Demand Progress. As of April 2026, Congress has not acted.

Some of the key architects of artificial intelligence have warned how the advent of AI dramatically heightens the risk of warrantless mass surveillance. Congress must act now to end warrantless location tracking and prevent the government from paying to bypass Fourth Amendment protections.

The loophole persists because the institutional architecture that Powell built is designed to ensure that it persists. The lobbying infrastructure delays legislation. The captured judiciary interprets existing law narrowly. The weakened regulatory agencies lack enforcement capacity. And the technology integrates more deeply into the infrastructure of daily life with each passing year, raising the cost of regulation and lowering the political will to attempt it. The industry understands this intuitively. The political spending is front-loaded: not to win the argument permanently but to delay meaningful oversight until the integration is irreversible. You do not need to defeat regulation if you can ensure that by the time it arrives, the thing it would regulate has become load-bearing. Regulating it then means disrupting systems that millions of people depend on — which makes the regulation politically impossible even if it is substantively necessary.

