## III. The Convergence Abroad: Three Models, One Trajectory

The American trajectory — Powell’s institutional capture producing the regulatory vacuum that produced the data broker loophole that produced warrantless mass surveillance — is not unique. The global trajectory reveals something more disturbing: a convergence across political systems that defies the stated justifications of each but produces the same material outcome. The models differ in their stated justifications — market freedom (US), competitiveness (EU), social harmony (China), financial inclusion (India) — but the material outcomes are trending in the same direction: states and corporations accumulating unprecedented surveillance capacity over populations with diminishing oversight.

### The European Retreat

The EU built the most comprehensive privacy framework in the world. The GDPR requires compliance by any entity that processes personal data in the context of activities of an “establishment” in the EU, or processes personal data of individuals in the EU related to the offering of goods or services to them or monitoring their behavior. There is no revenue threshold, processing threshold, or broker threshold. The consequences of noncompliance are administrative fines up to €20 million or 4% of total worldwide annual turnover of the preceding financial year, whichever is higher.

In the EU, data brokers fall within the scope of the GDPR, which applies to all entities that process personal data and does not differentiate data brokers from other data controllers or processors in terms of obligations. Under the GDPR, any processing of personal data must have a lawful basis such as consent, legitimate interests, or contractual necessity. European residents have the “right to be forgotten.” The regulation centers on “personal data,” which involves all information relating to identifiable individuals.

But the GDPR has structural gaps even in its existing form. The GDPR framework can leave both legal and conceptual gaps when it comes to weighing the role that other, less directly consumer-connected parties gather, process, generate, and transmit data, such as the potential lack of GDPR coverage when one broker sells data it did not collect itself to another data broker. The inferences that data brokers create and sell, such as by using location data to derive information about military service or children in the home, can also receive inadequate coverage under data protection law. European regulators enforcing these laws have remained steadily focused on American Big Tech companies like Meta and Alphabet. An overarching regulatory emphasis on certain large U.S. players may skew attention away from companies like data brokers — based both in the United States and in European countries. Many European regulators discussing regulation of “data” or “technology” in general often explicitly reference or implicitly mean the same group of Big Tech companies; companies like Google, Facebook, Instagram, TikTok, and now OpenAI occupy a prominent role in the European regulator imagination.

The data broker industry is very successful and active in the USA; the largest companies come from this region. Europe has also seen an increasing focus on address trading. Data brokers operate globally in a digital data ecosystem under different jurisdictions. The GDPR and other relevant European legislative acts, like the Digital Services Act, operate according to the principle of lex loci solutionis, thus applying to the activities of data brokers based outside the EU when they target European citizens. Even well-known data brokers from the USA, such as Acxiom, are subject to European regulation when operating in Europe. But the GDPR does not directly address the subject of data brokers or data trading. Data protection law is not aimed at restricting trade on the data economy; instead it provides for the protection of personal data as a consequence of the right to data protection. The commodification of personal information is the root of the informal and economic power imbalances in the digital world. Even though the GDPR’s regulatory framework is justly subject to much criticism, it theoretically offers a handhold against the business model of commercial data trading. As in many other areas, however, data protection law is subject to an enforcement deficit.

An RTÉ investigation in Ireland — the country’s national media broadcaster — described how reporters gained access to brokered data on tens of thousands of smartphones in Ireland that was on the market and available to purchase. The report found that individual devices could be traced as they traveled between residential addresses, high-security prisons, health clinics, mental health facilities, military bases, and even Leinster House, where the Irish parliament is located. Ireland’s Data Protection Commission said it is “extremely concerned.” This data brokerage in Europe is putting U.S. service members and personnel at risk. The U.S. is waiting on Europe to step in.

The United States is the only country to have legally ratified four data broker registries — in California, Oregon, Vermont, and Texas — with another four in development in New Jersey, Delaware, Michigan, and Alaska. The US has led the way in establishing data broker registries due to its fragmented approach to data privacy regulation, where states often take the initiative in passing consumer protection laws. Unlike the European Union, which enforces broad privacy protections under the GDPR, the US relies on state-level and sector-specific laws, creating a patchwork of regulations. With no such data broker registry for the European Union, EU data privacy enforcement could struggle to regulate the market when there is no central record for data brokers operating in its jurisdiction.

And now the GDPR itself is being actively weakened.

In November 2025, the European Commission published two Digital Omnibus proposals — Digital Omnibus and Digital Omnibus on AI — and opened a Digital Fitness Check, part of a sweeping deregulation agenda for EU digital policies. European Digital Rights described this as “a massive reopening of EU’s core digital protections — so far including the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), ePrivacy Directive and the Artificial Intelligence (AI) Act — a move that risks dismantling the very foundation of human rights and tech policy in the EU.”

The European Commission published the Digital Omnibus Regulation Proposal, which amends the GDPR in substance. The amendments would amend the purpose-limitation/further-processing rule in Article 5(1)(b); insert new articles on breach notification, refine aspects of Article 22 on automated decision-making, place storage of and access to information on end-user terminal equipment on an explicit GDPR framework via a new Article 88a, enable standardization around machine-readable preference/consent signalling via Article 88b, insert a new Article 88c on processing for development, testing, training, deployment and operation of machine-learning models, and insert a new Article 41a on implementing acts for pseudonymisation/identifiability criteria.

The European Data Protection Board and the European Data Protection Supervisor adopted a joint opinion. They “strongly urge the co-legislators not to adopt the proposed changes to the definition of personal data as they go far beyond a targeted or technical amendment of the GDPR. In addition, they do not accurately reflect and clearly go beyond the CJEU jurisprudence, and they would result in significantly narrowing the concept of personal data.” They specifically warned that “the European Commission should not be entrusted to decide by an implementing act what is no longer personal data after pseudonymisation as it directly affects the scope of application of EU data protection law.” The EDPB statement concluded: “Simplification is essential to cut red tape and strengthen EU competitiveness — but not at the expense of fundamental rights.”

According to a leaked draft of the EU member states’ decision on the Digital Omnibus, circulated by the Cypriot presidency of the Council and dated February 20, 2026, the Council of the European Union eliminates the proposed new definition of “personal data” under the GDPR. European Digital Rights Policy Advisor Itxaso Domínguez de Olazábal posted that the Commission’s proposed change “would have made it easier for actors in complex processing chains to argue that data is ‘not personal’ from their perspective.”

According to an analysis by Austrian privacy NGO noyb, the leaked draft of the Omnibus could significantly weaken GDPR protections. It narrows the definition of personal data, meaning information that cannot directly identify an individual might no longer count as personal, even if it could be linked with other data. This would strip many pseudonymous identifiers, such as ad IDs and cookies, of GDPR protection, paving the way for more tracking and profiling. The draft also limits when people can exercise their rights to access, correct, or delete data, restricting them to “data protection purposes.” In practice, this could block workers, journalists, or consumers from using data requests in disputes.

The Omnibus introduces a “legitimate interest” exception allowing companies to use personal data, including some sensitive information, for AI training, provided unspecified safeguards are in place. Under these rules, high-risk AI systems could process massive amounts of European data legally, while traditional data storage and processing, like databases or CCTV footage, remain tightly regulated. Noyb warns this could give US and global tech companies freer rein to use European data for AI training or analytics. In practice, EU users would rarely know their data is being used, and objections would be nearly impossible to enforce.

The long-delayed ePrivacy regulation, which controls how companies access data on users’ phones, computers, and other devices, could be merged into the GDPR under the Digital Omnibus. Currently, websites must get explicit consent before storing or accessing most cookies. Under the proposed changes, companies could collect some data without asking first, either for a limited list of “low-risk” uses or under a broader legal basis called “legitimate interest,” which lets companies argue they can use data if it serves their business. This would shift Europe from an opt-in system to something closer to opt-out, where users must actively refuse to stop tracking.

Article 22 of the GDPR provides strict limits ensuring that people are not subject to significant decisions made solely by automated systems without meaningful human involvement. The Omnibus reframes Article 22 as a broader permission for automation, giving firms more room to deploy automated systems in sensitive contexts where human review matters, weakening safeguards against unfair decisions. It also reduces the threshold for what counts as meaningful human involvement and turns a prohibition with exceptions into an authorisation subject to conditions. This shift makes it easier to rely on automation by default and harder for people to challenge decisions that significantly affect their lives.

The Digital Omnibus on AI tears the AI Act apart, undermining its key protections, including oversight and transparency mechanisms. Those making or selling AI systems could exempt themselves from fundamental rules, turning the EU’s flagship legislation into a “carte blanche” for high-risk algorithmic technologies. It delays the high-risk requirements without a clear timeline — caving to industry’s demands — and ultimately subverting the protections for people from AI harms and completely undermining legal certainty. The proposal weakens transparency, accountability and the role of fundamental rights bodies. This will leave people without effective redress when AI systems harm or discriminate against them.

EDRi stated: “Despite the Commission’s attempts to play down the issue, the Digital Omnibus is a full-on betrayal of Europe’s promise.”

The EFF stated that the GDPR “is the most comprehensive model for privacy legislation around the world. While it is far from perfect and suffers from uneven enforcement, complexities and certain administrative burdens, the omnibus package is full of bad and confusing ideas that, on balance, will significantly weaken privacy protections for users in the name of cutting red tape.” The EFF noted one positive element: requiring online interfaces to respect automated consent signals, allowing users to automatically reject consent across all websites instead of clicking through cookie popups. But “much as we love limiting cookie fatigue, it’s not worth the price users will pay if the rest of the proposal is adopted.”

Amnesty International described the Digital Omnibus as a situation where “corporations work hard to give regulation a bad name, but regulations protect our rights from being steamrolled by states and governments. They protect our environment, our rights at work, our rights online, and so much more. Backed by powerful corporations, the Commission’s so-called ‘Digital Omnibus’ threatens to weaken EU digital rules that were once seen as global benchmarks for privacy and AI. This plays on a false dichotomy between regulation and innovation, championed by Big Tech, who seek a rules-free environment that prioritizes profit at any cost.” Amnesty further noted: “Pressure is mounting across different areas of regulation, resulting in the rolling back of environmental protections, the weakening corporate governance and erosion of digital rights. It all amounts to a coordinated effort to weaken corporate accountability. Rolling back these protections puts all of us at risk.”

Technologist Robin Berjon warned that the proposed reforms “go beyond mere simplification. We’ve seen the European Commission be weak on enforcement and hesitant to anger the American authorities, but the omnibus changes go much further. American tech monopolies and intelligence agencies are the biggest beneficiaries of the surveillance economy and these changes strengthen their hand to instead actively sabotage European businesses and national security.”

The Commission’s Executive Vice President Henna Virkkunen met with top US tech executives to pitch a more business-friendly Europe and highlight plans to simplify digital rules. The reforms follow a report by former Italian Prime Minister Mario Draghi warning that Europe’s complex laws are stifling innovation and holding the region back in global competition with the US and China.

The outcome matters far beyond Europe. For a decade, the GDPR set a global standard for privacy that influenced laws in countries from Brazil to India and California. If Brussels now reverses course, the ripple effects could reshape how data protection and AI regulation are approached worldwide.

Itxaso Domínguez de Olazábal, writing in TechPolicy.Press, argued: “Changing core rules on privacy and data protection requires clear evidence and rigorous analysis. The Commission has provided neither. It did not publish a fundamental rights impact assessment, nor present data showing that current rules harm responsible firms. Similarly, it did not explain why enforcement challenges justify weakening rights. Even with proper procedure, some changes remain unacceptable. Laws tied to Article 7, the protection for private and family life, and Article 8, the protection of personal data, of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union safeguard people against both state and corporate intrusion and should not be lowered under any circumstances.”

If the GDPR falls — if the Digital Omnibus hollows out the framework — there is no major democratic government on earth with a comprehensive framework strong enough to matter. Brazil’s LGPD, India’s DPDP Act, and the other frameworks modeled on the GDPR lose their conceptual anchor. The global standard becomes a global floor that everyone races beneath.

### China and India

Ralph Schroeder’s research at Oxford identifies the Social Credit System in China and the Aadhaar system in India as “two cases of the most rapid capture of personal data about national populations in history.” So far, there is limited research about how the two systems operate in practice, on the ground. Yet for the longer-term shaping of the two systems — including notions of privacy, the role of the state in promoting digital technologies, and the relation among states, markets, and civil societies — there is extensive research to draw on.

China’s Social Credit System aims to establish a “sincerity culture” by rating trustworthiness and providing benefits to the trustworthy and punishing the untrustworthy. There is already a debate as to whether this marks the arrival of “digital dictatorship” in China ending its “fragmented authoritarianism” and to that extent is unique to that setting, or it marks the arrival of a “global age of algorithm” raising global concerns. China’s model is perhaps not an isolated case.

In 2024, the NDRC issued the 2024-2025 action plan, which foregrounds building more complete credit legislation (including pushing for a Social Credit Construction Law), improving unified codes, strengthening platform infrastructure and data security, and creating a more unified credit repair mechanism. In 2025, the NDRC and the PBOC issued the 2025 editions of the national basic catalogue of public credit information and the national basic list of disciplinary measures. These documents institutionalize a key governance theme: define the boundaries of public credit data and discipline, and reduce arbitrary expansion. In March 2025, a Party-and-State Council guideline explicitly targeted improvement of the social credit system with 23 measures and, in the official English summary, stressed safeguards around information security, individual rights, and guarding against excessive collection and illegal use of information.

New innovations in technology are playing a large role. AI facial recognition software is utilized in tandem with over 200 million surveillance cameras in China. The purpose of large-scale surveillance measures is to give Chinese officials the ability to track their citizens in every facet of everyday life, providing masses of data to determine whether an act worthy of being blacklisted has occurred. The government continues to track the online behaviors of its citizens.

It is sometimes imagined that the system automatically creates entries for individuals based on surveillance footage or other digital streams. This is not currently the case. All entries into an individual’s China social credit rating are manually entered and overseen by officials. Currently, there is no one “social credit score” that applies across all of China. There are many different social credit scores depending on the region or city. The system remains a work-in-progress that is fragmented between local and central governments regarding interpretation of policies and implementation. Many aspects of China’s social credit system have similarities with US scoring and penalty systems including FICO credit scores, tech rating systems (Uber, Airbnb), and historical precedents like the Hollywood blacklist of the 1940s and 1950s.

India’s Aadhaar — the world’s largest biometric identification system — issues a 12-digit number to every resident, generated after recording their demographic as well as biometric data such as fingerprints and iris scans. The program began in 2009 as a voluntary system. Its original purpose was to ensure access to welfare programs, to include the undocumented into the system so as to be able to correctly disseminate social benefits to the right individuals. In 2012, it became mandatory for all citizens; otherwise they would be denied entitlements and government services.

Despite claiming that participation was voluntary, the Indian government made Aadhaar mandatory for citizens to access a variety of social and financial services such as maintaining bank accounts and insurance policies, even for paying taxes. Still, even by 2017, there were hardly any legislative measures in place to protect the data being collected by the government and the technology companies that worked on its behalf. The project has raised fears of privacy violations and mass surveillance. Soon after it was launched, Indian intelligence officials said its purpose was to flush out illegal immigrants in the country — the reason why residents and not just citizens were asked to register for Aadhaar — and the claim that Aadhaar would help deliver welfare schemes was just a ruse. Security officials made attempts to use the Aadhaar database to find “criminals.”

India and China have launched enormous projects aimed at collecting vital personal information regarding their billion-plus populations and building the world’s biggest data sets in the process. Both Aadhaar and the Social Credit System are controversial and raise a plethora of political and ethical concerns. The governments claim that participation in these projects is voluntary, even as they link vital services to citizens registering with these projects. Topic modeling of news coverage suggests coverage in both nations disregards the public interest and focuses largely on how businesses can benefit from them. The media, institutionally and ideologically linked with governments and corporations, show little concern with violations of privacy and mass surveillance that these projects could lead to. Researchers argue that this renders citizens structurally incapable of making informed choices about participation.

The comparison between China and India points to the potential dangers of “big data” in ushering a surveillance state apparatus and the existence of blurred boundaries between democracy and authoritarianism when it comes to social control.

India’s Aadhaar biometric identification system, though different in purpose from China’s Social Credit System, raised comparable concerns about data privacy and state control. Russia’s increasing adoption of facial recognition surveillance technology to monitor citizens and political activists mirrors aspects of China’s practices. These developments underline the global trend toward increased digital surveillance, prompting crucial ethical and political discussions worldwide.

The distinction between a democratic government purchasing your location data from a broker and an authoritarian government collecting it directly is a distinction of method, not of outcome. The citizen is rendered transparent. The state is rendered opaque. The asymmetry is the same.

